{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d6aad325-1f01-4ad3-8796-4f0c39d9db98","content":"Here's how to collect a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace`:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n**3. Find your process and collect:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps                       # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio (`File → Open`) or [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container image, you can sidecar or pre-bake the tool into your image.\n- For **production-safe** continuous profiling, consider `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar container — it exposes an HTTP API for on-demand trace collection without exec'ing in.\n- Use `--providers Microsoft-DotNETCore-SampleProfiler` for CPU, or `gc-collect` profile for memory investigations.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bd6928e6-a91a-439f-8e7a-116be6aac1d4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":417},"id":"eea00108-bf8d-4dbc-be26-15e6e716e383","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:46:20.248Z","parentId":"d7d0574d-6320-455a-b8b7-d496c24d2683"}
